metadata.description:
Notes: GPU intensive. May not render on some mobile devices. Renders fastest with Chrome.

Controls:

Press 1-4 to change resolution:
1 - 1000px * 1410px

Default resolution is 1000px * 1410px. It is recommended to explore in 2000px * 2820px or above.

Paleterum (latin â€œplateâ€, â€œboardâ€) â€” a flat surface that is used by artists to hold and mix colors.
This artwork is an attempt to simulate the look of watercolor on paper. Inspired by childhood memories that passed through the watercolor sketches of my mother, who was an artist, the piece reflects my admiration for her work and her influence on my own artistic endeavors. 
Intricate forms contrast with the strict forms of cells. All these are echoes from childhood - watercolor lines of a child not bothered by a special artistic idea but trying at least to a fraction of mastering the fine arts and cubes reminiscent of ones which children use to build towers.
Overall, the piece is a tribute to the joy and creativity of childhood, and to the power of artistic inspiration that can be passed down from one generation to the next.

Made with p5js and a few GLSL shaders.

metadata.name: Blueprints of balance #42
metadata.description:
Balance in art is one of the basic principles of design, along with contrast, movement, rhythm, emphasis, pattern, unity, and variety. Balance refers to how the elements of art (line, shape, color, value, space, form, texture) relate to each other within the composition in terms of their visual weight to create visual equilibrium. That is, one side does not seem heavier than another.

But there is no balance without Chaos. And that is why for one hour everyday each Blueprint of balance let it go and turns into its alternative wild version.

metadata.name: Fantasized Telekinetic Obliteration #2
metadata.description:
An exploration on the ways in which mental energy might be captured and converted to kinetic destruction.

Each piece begins with an abstract shape. The shape is subjected to a field of disruptors, which contains a combination of beams and bombs. Beams slice through material, shearing fragments generally in the direction the beam is traveling. Bombs shatter material apart and eject shards away from the blast site.

All matter is conserved. That is, if the exploded and scattered fragments were reverted back to their initial positions, there would be a fully intact shape. No virtual particles. ðŸ–¤

Some structures may be annihilated. Others may take minor damage â€” or perhaps, none at all. Consult the â€œtelekinetic powerâ€ feature for a full assessment.

---
- made with p5js
- press â€œsâ€ to save png

metadata.name: Life has no scores #100
metadata.description:
We cannot compose life, at best we hum along to the melodies that life has been played in front of us. Looking back at the scores of our lives, the notations are never neatly noted, but fully felt.  Rewinding the songs of life are our memories, whether sad, happy, angry, or melancholy. It is not clear whether I am dreaming or awake, but our songs all do end. 

In this final drop (for ?), I have reused the first ever class calligraphy(){} I have written from my genesis drop â€œNothing comes from nothingâ€. As time passes, 10 drops later, across almost to the year, I am grateful for the progress I have made, as an artist, and more importantly as a human. After all, what is behind the code of generative art is a human being. 

Scores of music, scrolls of calligraphy, calendar or diary, notating life, time passes, and changes are inevitable. Sometimes we sing louder in laughter and joy, sometimes we scribble in uneasiness, sometimes we just get lost in neon lights. Life goes on. You and me, all the same and yet different.  

There are too many friend artists, friend collectors, fxhash team members, to thank for helping me through this journey. I would like to pay homage to Rudxane in this work, who has taken me under his wings, mentoring and encouraging me in art as well as showing me some degen stuff on the side:-). This homage is not copy-minting, or copying of styles, which I do not have the coding skills to do so even if I wanted to. But it is the influence of taste in many works of Rudxane. In a vague but agreeable taste, I present to you Life has no scores. 

What I was taught was disrupted, and grid studies left unfinished, and oh do we have a BINGO?

Tested on Chrome. Other browsers may render different or not at all (firefox)

Press â€˜2â€™ to save png.

metadata.name: paintflow #133
metadata.description:
For this project, I wanted to try out Ty Vek's SVG technique for creating gen art. I used some basic SVG filters to achieve the paint brush effect, then just added some simple line and curve patterns. The result is quite nice and organic feeling! There are only 2 colors: red and black - I felt it was important to focus on the shapes and lines rather than the colors. The number of curves varies from 2 to 4, and each can be filled above or below. That's the gist of it! I hope you get some pretty pieces.

You can save the generated SVG by pressing the 's' key, and you can save a PNG version by pressing the 'p' key.

Please enjoy!

metadata.name: ðŸðŸŒˆ Pixel Flags  #19
metadata.description:
A #genuary32nd project.

Colourful flags waving in a noisy breeze.


This is an expansion of my #genuary2023 Day 17 "A grid inside a grid inside a grid". The idea was to create a large-scale grid made up of the colours of a grid of pixels. Add disruptions for a 3-D effect, and voila, a flag! Though, the initial color grid might be very rare to generate, after all the features I've added for this Fx(hash) party.

This month provided me with an opportunity to improve my JavaScript and p5js skills. Coming from a rather static Python background, I was pleased to discover the broad possibilities of interaction and animation with p5js. For this reason, I chose to create an interactive yet contemplative work.

/// Press "P" to open the MENU \\\

You can play around with the controls to find the waving flag that suits your mood. Maybe you can even let it float on the beats of your music by checking the "Use Micro Input" box.
You can also set the different speeds and sizes. Of course, you can also record the canvas as a Gif or Png according to your disired size or length.


****
Created using p5js, the quicksettings library and what is contained in the boilerplate-p5js from TengilLejonhjarta
